This demo introduces the Case Analysis for Security Education (CASE) framework (https://cyber-cases.info/), an NSF funded initiative designed to enhance undergraduate cybersecurity education through realistic, scenario-based learning. CASE leverages real-world cybersecurity breaches and vulnerabilities to create structured case modules paired with discussion questions and hands-on lab exercises. These modules enable students to investigate authentic cyber incidents, analyze the technical and organizational factors that contributed to the compromise, and replicate attack and defense strategies within controlled virtual environments. Through this approach, students develop both adversarial thinking and systems thinking skills, strengthening their ability to understand complex threat landscapes and design effective security solutions. More than 30 CASE modules have been developed across eight thematic categories, including comprehensive breaches, ransomware and malware, web and cloud security, system and hardware exploits, social engineering, management and ethics, and emerging topics. Each module is designed to be modular, adaptable, and aligned with common cybersecurity learning outcomes, making CASE applicable to a wide range of courses in security, networking, systems, and software. This demo will guide participants through CASE modules and provide a walkthrough of the portal website. Participants will learn how to access, adopt, and adapt CASE modules for their own curricula and will gain practical insights into integrating case-based and experiential learning approaches into cybersecurity education. The demo aims to equip instructors with ready-to-use materials and effective strategies for enriching student engagement through authentic, evidence-based learning experiences. This research was supported by the NSF under Award No. 2247492.